Here is a simple Julia solution for this problem. The Statistics package is required and it can be added using Pkg.add("Statistics").

```julia
using Statistics

function weather_data_analyzer(temps)
    if isempty(temps)
        return (average = nothing, max = nothing, min = nothing, trend = nothing)
    end

    average_temp = mean(temps)
    max_temp = maximum(temps)
    min_temp = minimum(temps)

    if length(temps) < 2
        return (average = average_temp, max = max_temp, min = min_temp, trend = nothing)
    end

    trend_list = diff([min_temp; temps])
    if all(x -> x > 0, trend_list)
        return (average=average_temp, max=max_temp, min=min_temp, trend="increasing")
    elseif all(x -> x < 0, trend_list)
        return (average=average_temp, max=max_temp, min=min_temp, trend="decreasing")
    else
        return (average=average_temp, max=max_temp, min=min_temp, trend="stable")
    end
end
```
This function first checks if the list is empty. If it is, it returns a named tuple with all values set to nothing. 

If not, it calculates the average, maximum, and minimum temperatures using `mean`, `maximum`, and `minimum` functions from Statistics package. Then it uses a short list (with at least two elements) for trend analysis. If all differences in the list are positive, then it returns that the trend is increasing. If all differences are negative, then it returns that the trend is decreasing. If there's any mix of positive and negative values or if the list contains only one element, it returns that the trend is stable.

Remember to include Statistics package before running this function using `using Statistics`.
